\subsection{The hat game}
\label{sec:hat-game}

\fr{\ft{The hat game}
\begin{ex}[hat game]
  \begin{itemize}
  \item $n$ players and each one wears a hat
  \item hat can be
    either black or white
  \item  Each player observes the other player's hat
    color but not his own!
  \item several rounds: In each round, those players who know the colour of their own hat for sure raise their hand.
  \end{itemize}
Does anyone ever raise his hand? 
%No!
\begin{itemize}
\item Say, you see: $\triangle$
  \begin{Large}
    $\blacktriangle$
  \end{Large}
$\triangle$
\item 1st round: will you raise your hand?
\item 2nd round: if no one raised hand in first round, will you raise hand? what if $k$ players raised hand in 1st round?
\item etc.
\end{itemize}
\end{ex}

\begin{ex}[hat game variation]
  \begin{itemize}
  \item outside observer announces truthfully before the first round:
    ``At least one of you wears a black hat.''
  \item If $k$ people wear a black hat, will anyone raise his hand? Who and in which round?
  \end{itemize}
Say you see: $\triangle$
  \begin{Large}
    $\blacktriangle$
  \end{Large}
$\triangle$
\begin{itemize}
\item 1st round: raise hand or not?
\item 2nd round: 
  \begin{itemize}
  \item if no one raised hand in round 1: raise hand now?
  \item if 1 player raised hand in round 1: raise hand now?
  \end{itemize}
\item who will raise hand in 3rd round?
\end{itemize}
\end{ex}

\framebreak
Let's look at $n$ players, $k\leq n$ of which have a black hat: 
    For general $n$:
    \begin{itemize}
    \item If k=1, in which round does the black hat wearer know?\\
   In which round do the white hat wearer know?
    \item If k=2, which round do the black hats know?\\
    Which round the white hats?
   \item If k=3,\dots
    \end{itemize}

\framebreak

\begin{result}
  In round $k$, everyone with a black hat raises his hand. In round
  $k+1$ everyone else raises his hand.
\end{result}



\begin{itemize}
\item take a situation with $k\geq 2$
\item observer does not give any new information to any player when saying that there is at least 1 black hat
\item  outcome is completely different!
\item observer does not create knowledge but makes sure that knowledge is \emph{common knowledge}
\end{itemize}

