  The problem in the example is that the posteriors are not \emph{common knowledge}:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item P2 does not know what P1 thinks what $\eta_2(E)$ is:
    \begin{itemize}
    \item for example $\omega_3\in P_2(\omega')$ but in $\omega_3$ P1 does not know P2's posterior% P1 would belief with prob $1/2$ that $\eta_2(E)$
      % is $1/3$ (this is in $\omega_3$) and with prob $1/2$ that
      % $\eta_2(E)=1$ (this is in $\omega_4$)
    \end{itemize}
 % Put differently, player 2 knows his
    % posterior and player 1's posterior but he does not know that
    % player 1 knows his posterior!

    \item formally: take the event $F$: ``player 2's posterior for the event $E$ is 1/3''
      \begin{itemize}
      \item $F$ ``happens'' in the states $\omega_1$, $\omega_2$ and $\omega_3$
      \item $K_1(F)=\{\omega_1,\omega_2\}$ and
        $K_2(K_1(F))=\emptyset$
      \item F is not common knowledge  although both players know $F$ in state $\omega_1$
      \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
