\begin{prop}
  Let $G$ be a 2 player game and assume that in state $\omega$ it is common knowledge that each player's belief are consistent with his knowledge and that each player is rational.\\ Technically, suppose that there is a self-evident $F$ with $\omega\in F$ such that for any $\omega'\in F$ and each $i\in N$
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item the support of $\mu_i(\omega')$ is a subset of $\{a_j(\omega''): \omega''\in P_i(\omega')\} $
  \item the action $a_i(\omega')$ is a best response of $i$ given $\mu_i(\omega')$.
  \end{enumerate}
Then $a_i(\omega)$ is rationalizable in $G$.
\end{prop}
