\textbf{Real email game}
\begin{itemize}
\item if the game is b, P1's computer will automatically(!) send a
  message to P2's computer
\item if the game is a: no message
\item every message (by any player) is automatically (!)
  confirmed by the recepients computer with another message%  to the sender computer,
  % i.e. not only for the original message but also for confirmation
  % messages. However
\item  there is a small probability $\varepsilon>0$ that
  any given message is lost and does therefore not arrive% . If a message
  % does not arrive, the communication stops. 
\item before taking their actions, both players see the number of messages that their computer sent away
\end{itemize}

\framebreak

Formalization of email game::
\begin{itemize}
\item  State space is $\Omega=\{(q_1,q_2):q_1=q_2\text{ or }q_1=q_2+1,\; q_i\in \mathbb{N}\}$% , i.e. in state (q,q) each player's computer sends q messages and then a message by player 2 is lost, in state (q+1,q) a message by player 1 is lost
\item $P_1(q,q)=P_1(q,q-1)=\{(q,q),(q,q-1)\}$ for $q\geq 1$ and $P_1(0,0)=\{(0,0)\}$ 
\item $P_2(q,q)=P_2(q+1,q)=\{(q,q),(q+1,q)\}$
\item the game played: $G(0,0)=a$ and b otherwise
\item prior belief over $\Omega$ derived from the technology: $p_i(0,0)=1-p$ (i.e. game a with prob 1-p); $p_i(q+1,q)=p\varepsilon (1-\varepsilon )^{2q}$ and $p_i(q+1,q+1)=p\varepsilon (1-\varepsilon )^{2q+1}$
\end{itemize}

\framebreak

First analysis:
\begin{itemize} 
\item P2 knows the game in all states apart from (0,0) and (1,0).
\item if the game is b, P1 does not know that P2 knows the game in states (1,0) and (1,1). Otherwise, P1 knows that P2 knows.
\item in states, (1,1) and (2,1) P2 knows the game but does not know whether P1 knows that P2 knows \dots
\end{itemize}

