\item Let $\tilde q_i$ be the lowest number of own sent messages for which player $i$ plays B in a given equilibrium and suppose at least one of them is finite. We will show that this leads to a contradiction. 
  \begin{itemize}
  \item $\tilde q_1> \tilde q_2$: Otherwise, P1 finds it optimal to play A when reading $\tilde q_1$ contradicting that we are in equilibrium: \dots% obvious if $\tilde q_1<\tilde q_2$; if equality than it is more likely that own message got lost than that P2's message got lost and therefore P2 is mor elikely to play A than B
  \item when reading $\tilde q_2$, P2 must weakly prefer B over A; however\dots%knowing that $\tilde q_1> \tilde q_2$, P2 believes that P1 is more likely to play A than B which implies that he prefers B
